{
  "texts": [
    "Assume that f is a B-map.",
    "In view of Lemma 3.2.3 (iii), for anyS ⊂ I, ⌢ A s ≠ ∅ implies ⌢ B s ≠ ∅ so that κ a ⊂ κ b. Conversely first select for any S ∈ κ b an element b s ∈ B s. If κ a ⊂ κ b,one can define a map on A by positing for any a ∈ ⌢ A s f (a) ∶= b s. In view of Lemma 3.2.3 (ii), f is clearly a BG-map.",
    "◻ Two p-sites a and b with the same base I, are said to be BG-isomorphic if there is a BG-map f ∶ a → b and a BG-map g ∶ b → a.",
    "▽ It follows from the above that a and b are BG-isomorphic if and only if κ a = κ b Let a ≡ ( (I, A, (A i))) and b ≡ ( (I, B, (B i))) be two p-sites, f ∶ a → b a surjective BG-map.",
    "There exists a right inverse g ∶ B → A to the function f ( f ○ g = id B)."
  ]
}